Subject: in_dxf: fix crashes and aborts importing AutoCAD dynamic-block DXFs

Importing a real AutoCAD 2018 DXF using dynamic blocks (BLOCKSTRETCHACTION,
ACAD_EVALUATION_GRAPH, FIELD) either segfaulted or aborted the whole file.
Four fixes:

* src/in_dxf.c (add_EVAL_Node): reset the per-node 92-counter when a new
  node starts (91). Each node carries four 92 group codes; without the
  reset the second node's first 92 was misread as the start of the edge
  list, deraililng the parse into "Invalid DXF code 92" and aborting the
  import.
  Also: group 95 is the node's nextid per dwg.spec; it was clobbering
  edge_flags and warning "!= 32" on perfectly valid files.
* src/in_dxf.c (add_EVAL_Edge): realloc with (i + 1), not num_edges,
  which is still 0 on the first edge: realloc to 0 bytes made the
  edges[0] write a heap overflow.
* src/in_dxf.c (add_AcDbBlockStretchAction): the hdls[i].indexes and
  codes[i].indexes arrays were never allocated before being written to
  (SEGV at in_dxf.c:8619), and the codes loop bound was copy-pasted
  from hdls[i].num_indexes.
* src/in_dxf.c (add_FIELD): AutoCAD writes each childval's data type as
  group 93 (not 90), with optional typed payload pairs, 300/302 format
  strings and a "304 ACVALUE_END" terminator, and appends the evaluated
  cache value under a 7 key. The strict 90-based reader aborted the
  import ("Invalid DXF code 93 for FIELD"). Parse the value block
  tolerantly, accepting both this layout and the legacy 90-based one.

With these, a 4.5 MB real-world pavement plan (AutoCAD 2018, dynamic
blocks) converts dxf2dwg --as r2000 cleanly and the result opens in
ezdxf and AutoCAD-compatible viewers. All 254 unit tests pass.

Co-authored-by: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>


